  "content": "_G.R. Bhat et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                         Results in Control and Optimization 14 (2024) 100401_ \n\nof standards for operating them. A difference in drone aviation standards is observed through countries and states [3]. The difference in these standards is caused due to several factors such as terrain, infrastructure, and altitude. These standards decide factors such as maximum flying altitude, frequency of operation, etc., and directly impact the drone’s weight, materials, hardware, and software. Fig. 1 shows a visual representation of the regulations in a few major countries promoting research in the area of drones. \n\nToday, the application in addition use of drones is increasing rapidly [1]. Besides commercial purposes, UAVs are designed according to various applications such as agriculture, archaeological research, education, civil surveys, and defence [2]. However, they require a set of standards for operating them. A difference in drone aviation standards is observed through countries and states [3]. The difference in these standards is caused due to several factors such as terrain, infrastructure, and altitude. These standards decide factors such as maximum flying altitude, frequency of operation, etc., and directly impact the drone’s weight, materials, hardware, and software [4]. Fig. 1 shows a visual representation of the regulations in a few major countries promoting research in the field of drones. \n\nBaassi et al. [5] stated that the operating height and weight factors discussed in Fig. 1 affect aerial locomotion. Global standardization of aviation rules and regulations is a challenge. Drones require a license to fly and require a pilot to have a license to operate. At times, drone operators require permission to fly drones on private property. These laws are introduced to avoid often happening accidents in flight, both in the military and commercial UAVs [6]. These challenges are addressed by implementing closed-loop control systems on various drone components [7]. Automated drones are possible due to closed-loop control systems. An autonomous flight is possible due to automated individual parts of drones. The key purpose of an autonomous drone is to lessen human input and error through the help of Machine Learning (ML) and Artificial Intelligence (AI) [8]. Carev, et al. [9], invented a universal metric to measure research programs, planning innovative programs, and comparing efforts to develop autonomous control technology. This metric is known as the Autonomous Control Level (ACL) for a UAV. The ACL metric system was made by Air Force Research Laboratory’s Air Vehicles Directorate. Most UAVs today which are operational commonly do not rank high on the ACL metric [10]. Fig. 2, shows the levels of autonomy and the trends followed according to ACL metrics. \n\nIn this paper, the correlation between the varying regulations for UAVs around the world and their levels of autonomy are dis’Motors and cussed. It explores the definitions, functionalities, current research, and challenges of achieving ACL 10 UAVs. Section propellors’, offers a summary of the essential components of a UAV, including motors and propellers that facilitate flight and enable adaptation to different flight conditions. Section ’Flight control and ESC’ describes the data processing unit, flight controller, and electronic speed controller of the UAV. Section ’Vision and mapping’ discusses the importance of visual input for autonomy and surveys the most widely used technologies for mapping and visualizing environments. Section ’Communication’, covers the current communication layer in UAVs, emphasizing its importance in establishing tactical and strategic commands for groups of drones. Section ’Path planning’ focuses on path planning, including current methodologies for allowing drones to think for themselves and plan or reroute their trajectories. Section ’Simulation’ emphasizes the role of simulation in achieving a fully autonomous swarm, while Section ’Conclusion’ concludes the paper. \n\n## **Motors and propellors** \n\nBLDC motors are essential in today’s mechanical applications. These motors are preferred because of their high-power efficiency and density. The power yield of BLDCs can be limited by varying the voltage applied to ESCs [11]. In accordance with the fundamental principles governing electric motors, the resultant mechanical power (P) is evaluated by considering M as the torque which is measured in Newton-meters (Nm), ω as the angular velocity which is expressed in radians per second (rad/s), and n as the rotational speed denoted in revolutions per minute (RPM) [12]. Propellers are coupled on top of these motors that provide lift to the aircraft by spinning and generating airflows which further accelerate mass in one direction, counteracting the force of gravity [13]. An increase in temperature in BLDC motors due to high payload results in anomalies in the motor, making the drone go out of control or crash [14]. Another widespread problem in UAVs is damage to the propellors and motors due to the collection of dust or soil, and impact on crash-landings [15]. To avoid further complications and failure in motors, monitoring their temperatures becomes the first concern [16]. \n\nMultiple anomaly detection and temperature sensing systems are developed and implemented in motors to tackle complications caused due to high temperature [17]. In anomaly detection systems, reinforcement learning models are used to continuously detect the \n\n**Fig. 1.** Regulations in prominent countries regarding weight (grams) and height (meter). \n\n2 \n\n",
